<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="s_primitive_roots" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Primitive roots</title>
   <subsection xml:id="ss_order_primitive_roots">
    <title>Order and primitive roots</title>
    <p>
        Recall Euler's theorem: if <m>n</m> is a positive integer and <m>a\in \Z</m> is relatively prime to <m>n</m>, then <m>a^{\phi(n)}\equiv 1 \pmod n</m>. Equivalently, in the language of modular rings, given <m>r=[a]_n\in (\Z/n\Z)^*</m>, we have <m>r^{\phi(n)}=[a]_n^{\phi(n)}=1</m>. As an illustration of the economy of the modular ring language, let's re-prove this result.
    </p>
    <proof>
        <title>Modular ring proof of Euler's theorem</title>
        <p>
         Let <m>n</m> be a positive element, and let <m>r_1,r_2,\dots, r_{\phi(n)}</m> be the distinct elements of <m>(\Z/n\Z)^*</m>, so that 
         <md>
            <mrow>(\Z/n\Z)^* \amp = \{r_1,r_2,\dots, r_{\phi(n)}\}</mrow>
         </md>. 
         (Note: although we have <m>r_i=[a_i]_n</m> for some integer <m>a_i</m>, we will not need to make use of these integers in our argument; we will only use properties of <m>(\Z/n\Z)^*</m> discussed in the previous section.) 
        </p>
        <p>
            Now, given any element <m>r\in (\Z/n\Z)^*</m>, we claim that we have the set equality 
            <md>
                <mrow>\{r_1,r_2,\dots, r_{\phi(n)}\} \amp = \{r\,r_1, r\, r_{2},\dots, r\, r_{\phi(n)}\}</mrow>
            </md>.
            Indeed, from <xref ref="th_units_mod_n"/>, we know that <m>r\, r_i\in (\Z/n\Z)^*</m>, since <m>(\Z/n\Z)^*</m> is closed under multiplication. Thus 
            <md>
                <mrow>\{r\,r_1, r\,r_2,\dots, r\,r_{\phi(n)}\} \amp\subseteq (\Z/n\Z)^*=\{r_1,r_2,\dots, r_{\phi(n)}\} </mrow>
            </md>.
            For the other inclusion, we use the fact that there is an element <m>r^{-1}\in (\Z/n\Z)^*</m> satisfying <m>r\,r^{-1}=1</m>. Given any element <m>r_i\in (\Z/n\Z)^*</m>, letting <m>r_j=r^{-1}\cdot r_i</m>, we have 
            <md>
                <mrow>r\,r_j \amp = r(r^{-1}r_i)</mrow>
                <mrow> \amp = (rr^{-1})r_i</mrow>
                <mrow> \amp = 1r_i</mrow>
                <mrow> \amp = r_i</mrow>
            </md>.
            Having shown <m>\{r_1,r_2,\dots, r_{\phi(n)}\}=\{rr_1,rr_2,\dots, rr_{\phi(n)}\}</m>, we see that 
            <md>
                <mrow>\prod_{i=1}^{\phi(n)}r_i \amp =\prod_{i=1}^{\phi(n)}rr_i</mrow>
                <mrow> \amp = r^{\phi(n)}\prod_{i=1}^{\phi(n)}r_i</mrow>
            </md>.
            Letting <m>s=\prod_{i=1}^{\phi(n)}r_i</m>, the above equality becomes 
            <md>
                <mrow>s \amp =r^{\phi(n)}s</mrow>
            </md>.
            Since <m>s\in (\Z/n\Z)^*</m>, it can be cancelled multiplicatively by multiplying both sides by <m>s^{-1}</m>. We conclude that <m>1=r^{\phi(n)}</m>, as desired. 
        </p>
    </proof>
    <definition xml:id="d_order_modular_unit">
    <title>Order of a modular unit</title>
    <notation>
        <usage><m>\ord r</m></usage>
      <description>order of element <m>r\in (\Z/n\Z)^*</m></description>
    </notation>
    <statement>
    <p>
    Let <m>n</m> be a positive integer. Given an element <m>r\in (\Z/n\Z)^*</m>, its <term>order</term> is the smallest positive integer <m>k</m> such that <m>r^k=1</m>. 
    </p>
    <p>
    Similarly, given an integer <m>a\in \Z</m> that is relatively prime to <m>n</m>, the <term>order of <m>a</m> modulo <m>n</m></term> is the smallest positive integer <m>k</m> such that <m>a^k\equiv 1\pmod n</m>.
    </p>
    </statement>
    </definition>
    <remark>
    <title>Modular exponentiation</title>
    <p>
    In what follows we will take for granted some elementary algebraic properties about exponentiation in <m>\Z/n\Z</m> that follow immediately from the corresponding properties in <m>\Z</m>. For example, we have 
    <md>
        <mrow>r^{j+k} \amp = r^jr^k \amp r^{jk}=(r^j)^k=(r^k)^j</mrow>
    </md>
    for all <m>r\in \Z/n\Z</m> and nonnegative integers <m>j,k\in \Z_{\geq 0}</m>. Furthermore, if <m>r\in (\Z/n\Z)^*</m>, then definining negative powers as <m>r^{-n}=(r^{-1})^n</m>, the above equalities hold for all integers <m>j,k\in \Z</m>. 
    </p>
    </remark>
    
    <proposition xml:id="prop_order_mod_n">
        <title>Order of modular units</title>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Let <m>n</m> be a positive integer, let <m>r\in (\Z/n\Z)^*</m>, and let <m>m=\ord r</m>. 
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                           For all integers <m>k</m>, <m>r^k=1</m> if and only if <m>m\mid k</m>. 
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>r^i=r^j</m> if and only if <m>i\equiv j\pmod m</m>. 
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            We have 
                            <md>
                                <mrow>\{r^i\mid i\in \Z\} \amp = \{1,r,r^2,\dots, r^{m-1}\}</mrow>
                            </md>,
                            and this set has cardinality <m>m</m> (<ie/>, it contains exactly <m>m</m> distinct elements). 
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>\ord r^i=m/\gcd(i,m)</m> for all integers <m>i\in \Z</m>. 
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </statement>
        <proof>
            <p>
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            First assume that <m>m\mid k</m>, so that <m>k=mq</m> for some <m>q\in \Z</m>. We then have 
                            <md>
                                <mrow>r^k \amp =r^{mk}</mrow>
                                <mrow> \amp = (r^m)^k</mrow>
                                <mrow> \amp =1^k=1</mrow>
                            </md>,
                            as desired. Conversely, 
                            assume <m>r^k=1</m> and write <m>k=qm+s</m> where <m>0\leq s &lt; m</m>, as in the division algorithm. Since 
                            <md>
                                <mrow>0 \amp =r^{k}</mrow>
                                <mrow> \amp = r^{qm+s}</mrow>
                                <mrow> \amp = r^{qm}r^s</mrow>
                                <mrow> \amp =r^s \amp (m\mid qm)</mrow>
                            </md>,
                            and since <m>m</m> is the smallest <em>positive</em> integer satisfying <m>r^m=1</m>, we must have <m>s=0</m>, and thus <m>m\mid k</m>. 
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            We have 
                            <md number="yes">
                                <mrow>r^i=r^j \amp \iff r^{i}r^{-j}=r^{j}r^{-j}</mrow>
                                <mrow> \amp \iff r^{i-j}=1</mrow>
                                <mrow> \amp \iff m\mid (i-j) \amp (\text{by } (1))</mrow>
                                <mrow> \amp \iff i\equiv j\pmod m</mrow>
                            </md>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Since <m>r^i=r^j</m> if and only if <m>i\equiv j\pmod m</m>, and since <m>\{0,1,\dots, m-1\}</m> form a complete set of residues modulo <m>m</m>, we have 
                            <md number="yes">
                                <mrow>\{r^i\mid i\in \Z\} \amp = \{r^0, r^1,\dots, r^{m-1}\} </mrow>
                                <mrow> \amp =\{1,r,\dots, r^{m-1}\}</mrow>
                            </md>,
                            and these powers of <m>r</m> are all distinct. Thus the set has cardinality <m>m</m>. 
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Let <m>k=m/\gcd(i,m)</m>. We will show that <m>k</m> is the smallest positive integer such that <m>(r^i)^k=1</m>, and thus that <m>\ord r^i=k</m>.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            First observe that <m>(r^{i})^k=r^{ik}=r^{(i/\gcd(i,m))m}=1</m>, since <m>m\mid (i/\gcd(i,m))m</m>. Now assume that <m>\ell</m> is a positive integer satisfying <m>(r^i)^\ell=r^{i\ell}=1</m>. It follows that <m>m\mid i\ell</m>. But then 
                            <md>
                                <mrow>m\gcd(i,m) \amp \mid (i/\gcd(i,m))\ell</mrow>
                            </md>.
                            Since <m>m/\gcd(i,m)</m> and <m>i/\gcd(i,m)</m> are relatively prime, it follows that <m>k=m/\gcd(i,m)\mid \ell</m>, and hence that <m>k\leq \ell</m>, since <m>k</m> and <m>\ell</m> are positive. This proves <m>k</m> is the smallest positive integer such that <m>(r^i)^k=1</m>, and thus that <m>\ord r^i=k</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </proof>
    </proposition>
    <definition xml:id="d_cyclic_group">
    <title>Primitive root</title>
    <statement>
    <p>
    Let <m>n</m> be a positive integer, and let <m>r\in (\Z/n\Z)^*</m>. The <term>cyclic group generated by <m>r</m></term>, denoted <m>\langle r\rangle</m>, is the set of all integer powers of <m>r</m>: <ie/>, 
    <md>
        <mrow>\angvec{r} \amp = \{r^i\mid i\in \Z\}</mrow>
        <mrow> \amp = \{1,r, \dots, r^{m-1}\}</mrow>
    </md>,
    where <m>m=\ord r</m>. 
    </p>
    <p>
        A <term>primitive root</term> (or <term>cyclic generator</term>) of <m>(\Z/n\Z)^*</m> is an element <m>r\in (\Z/n\Z)^*</m> satisfying <m>\angvec{r}=(\Z/n\Z)^*</m>. 
    </p>
    </statement>
    </definition>
    <example xml:id="eg_primitive_roots">
    <title>Primitive roots</title>
    <statement>
    <p>
    Decide for the given modulus <m>n</m> whether <m>(\Z/n\Z)^*</m> has a primitive root. 
    <ol>
        <li>
            <p>
                <m>n=7</m>
            </p>
        </li>
        <li>
            <p>
                <m>n=12</m>
            </p>
        </li>
        <li>
            <p>
                <m>n=25</m>
            </p>
        </li>
    </ol>
    </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
    <p>
    
    </p>
    </solution>
    </example>
    
    </subsection>
    <subsection xml:id="ss_polynomials_Fp">
    <title>Polynomials over a ring</title>
    <p>
        We now make a small digression to develop some notions about polynomials with coefficients in a given number system. We could develop this theory for polynomials with coefficients in an arbitrary ring <m>R</m>, but since we have not given an official definition of a ring, we will restrict ourselves to the case where our coefficients lie in <m>\Z</m>, <m>\Q</m>, <m>\R</m>, or <m>\Z/n\Z</m> for some positive integer <m>n</m>.
    </p>
    <definition xml:id="d_polynomials">
    <title>Polynomials over a ring</title>
    <statement>
    <p>
    Let <m>R</m> be either <m>\Z</m>, <m>\Q</m>, <m>\R</m>, or <m>\Z/n\Z</m> for some positive integer <m>n</m>. A <term>polynomial over <m>F</m> in the indeterminate (or variable) <m>x</m></term> is a formal expression of the form 
<md>
    <mrow>f(x) \amp =a_nx^n+a_{n-1}x^{n-1}+\cdots a_1x+a_0</mrow>
</md>,
where <m>n</m> is a nonnegative integer and <m>a_i\in F</m> for all <m>0\leq i\leq n</m>. We call <m>a_i</m> the <term>coefficients</term> of <m>f</m>. The polynomial is <term>nonzero</term> if <m>a_i\ne 0</m> for some <m>i</m>, and <term>zero</term> otherwise. The <term>degree</term> of a nonzero polynomial <m>f</m>, denoted <m>\deg f</m>, is the largest positive integer <m>n</m> such that the <m>n</m>-th coefficient of <m>f</m> is nonzero. 
</p>
    <p>
         Two nonzero polynomial <m>f(x)=\anpoly</m> and <m>g(x)=bmpoly</m> with <m>a_n\ne 0</m> and <m>b_m\ne 0</m> are equal, written <m>f=g</m> if <m>n=m</m> and <m>a_i=b_i</m> for all <m>0\leq i\leq n</m>. 
    </p>
    <p>
        Given a polynomial <m>f(x)=\anpoly</m> and an element <m>r\in F</m>, the <term>evaluation of <m>f</m> at <m>r</m></term> is the element <m>f(r)</m> defined as 
        <md number="yes">
            <mrow>f(r) \amp = a_nr^n+a_{n-1}r^{n-1}+\cdots a_1r+a_0 </mrow>
        </md>.
        In this manner, the polynomial <m>f</m> defines a function <m>f\colon R\rightarrow R</m>. An element <m>r\in F</m> is a <term>root</term> of <m>f</m> if <m>f(r)=0</m>. 
    </p>
    <p>
        Lastly, addition and multiplication of polynomials are defined as usual. In particular, given <m>f(x)=\anpoly</m> and <m>g(x)=\bmpoly</m>, we have 
        <md number="yes">
            <mrow xml:id="eq_poly_mult">f(x)g(x) \amp =c_{n+m}x^{n+m}+\cdots +c_1x+c_0</mrow>
        </md>,
            where 
            <md number="yes">
                <mrow xml:id="eq_poly_mult_coeff">c_k \amp =\sum_{i=0}^ka_ib_{k-i}</mrow>
            </md>
            for all <m>0\leq k\leq n+m</m>.
    </p>
    </statement>
    </definition>
    
       
    <p>
        Although we stated our definitions for polynomials over general rings, for the next theorem we need to restrict ourselves to the case where the coefficients lie in a field. Again, since we have not given a definition of a field, we will state the results for polynomials with coeffiecients in <m>\Q</m>, <m>\R</m>, or <m>\F_p</m> for some prime integer <m>p</m>.
    </p>
    <theorem xml:id="th_polynomials_props">
    <title>Polynomial properties</title>
    <statement>
    <p>
    Let <m>F</m> be either <m>\F_p</m> for some prime integer <m>p</m>, <m>\Q</m>, or <m>\R</m>, and let <m>f</m> and <m>g</m> be nonzero polynomials over <m>F</m>. 
    <ol>
        <li>
            <title>Degree of products</title>
            
            
            <p>
                <m>\deg fg=\deg f+\deg g</m>.
            </p>
        </li>
        <li>
            <title>Division with remainder</title>
            <p>
               There are unique polynomials <m>q</m> and <m>r</m> such that <m>f(x)=q(x)g(x)+r(x)</m> and either <m>r(x)=0</m> or <m>0\leq \deg r&lt; \deg g </m>.
            </p>
        </li>
        <li>
            <title>Roots and factorization</title>
            <p>
                An element <m>r\in F</m> is a root of <m>f</m> if and only if we have <m>f(x)=(x-r)g(x)</m> for some polynomial <m>g</m>. 
            </p>
        </li>
        <li>
            <title>Roots and degree</title>
            <p>
                Let <m>\deg f=n</m>. There are at most <m>n</m> distinct roots of <m>f</m> in <m>F</m>. 
            </p>
        </li>
    </ol>
    </p>
    </statement>
    <proof>
    <p>
    </p>
    </proof>
    </theorem>
    
    </subsection>
</section>